Installing devtools

devtools is a R package that allows interacting with package that are under development and are not part of cran. If you are on Windows, before installing devtools you need to install Rtools. Rtools is a program that installs a set of utilities that are needed by R when using in conjunction with devtools.

To install Rtools, point your browser to http://cran.r-project.org/bin/windows/Rtools/ and install the version that is compatible with your version of R. For instance, if you have installed R 3.2.x and later versions you need to install Rtools 3.3. While this is the most likely scenario check R version before installing.

Once installation of Rtools succeeded, you can turn to installation of devtools. This is done by

install.packages("devtools")

If everything worked fine, you should be able to load your package

library(devtools)

This step are meant to be executed only once. You do not need to install Rtools and devtools every time you start R.

Updating installed packages

The stock installation of R has few packaged installed. These packages are required by R to work properly. However, these packages are updated frequently to fix bugs and improve they capabilities. This is also true for other packages that you may have installed on your computer.

To update all packages that are installed on your computer

update.packages(ask = FALSE)

This command will download and install new versions of the packages installed. The option ask = FALSE prevents R to ask the user consent for the installation of each package. If for example, you do not want to install a specific package you should pass ask = TRUE to update.packages (or, since it is the default option, not pass anything at all) and say N to the package you do not want to be updated.

Installing ase

The ase package is installed by issuing the following commands

update.packages(ask = FALSE)
library(devtools)
# you do not need the previous command if you already loaded 
# the library in the same session and already unpdate the installed packages
install_github("gragusa/ase")

You should now be able to load the ase library

library(ase)

Loading dataset from the ase package

The ase package comes with almost all dataset that we will use during the course. They way dataset are loaded into R is by using the data function. For instance, to load the ceo dataset, you execute:

Individual variables can be accessed in many ways. For instance, the variable salary can be accessed by ceo$salary. Alternatively, using ceo['salary']. These two ways return an integer, while accessing ceo[['salary']] return a data.frame with only one variable. Usually it is not important how the variable is accessed, unless one really cares about the class of the returning object. For instance, if one wants to calculate statistics on the variable ceo['salary'] won’t work.

median(ceo$salary)
## [1] 1032.5
median(ceo[['salary']])
## [1] 1032.5
median(ceo['salary']) ## Try this yourself --- it won't work

You can also use the attach function to directly access the variable in the dataset.

attach(ceo)
mean(salary)
## [1] 1282.014
detach(ceo)

In this case, mean will find salary since ceo has been attached (to the search path). detach instead remove ceo from the search path. Using attach/detach is however dangerous should never be used (unless there is a reason for it). A better way to deal with accessing variables in a data.frame is to use with to run a command on element of a data.frame. For instance,

with(ceo, mean(salary))
## [1] 1282.014

works because mean uses ceo as a place to look for the variable salary.

Basic plotting functions

The main plotting facility in R is the plot function. For instance, to produce a scatterplot

plot(ceo$roe, y=ceo$salary)

Of course, the graph is not very pretty, but can be made nicer by tinkering with the plot options (there are many many options!)

plot(ceo$pcroe, y=ceo$salary, main = "Scatterplot", xlab = "return on equity", ylab = "salary", pch = 20, col = "darkred")

An histogram of salary can be obtained by using

with(ceo, hist(salary))

hist try to figure out the optimal number of breaks between histogram cells. This can be adjusted in several ways. You can pass the number of breaks breaks = 15, or the breaks breaks = seq(0, 14821, 2000), or use an automatic algorithm by passing to breaks one of the three algorithms: sturges, scott, and fd.

with(ceo, hist(salary, breaks = 15))
with(ceo, hist(salary, breaks = c(0, 200, 740, 1400, 2400, 5000, 14822)))
with(ceo, hist(salary, breaks = "scott"))

The default histogram produces a count of the number of observations in each cell. To have instead the density of each bin the option prob = TRUE must be used.

h <- with(ceo, hist(salary, prob = TRUE))  ## Notice the assignment

The density values annoted on the y axis of the histogram are small because the are the number of observations in each beans divided the total number of observations divided again by the width of each bin. This means that the densities multiplied by the width of its own bin sum to 1. To see this, notice that in the above call we have assigned to h the output of with(ceo, hist(salary, prob = TRUE)). That is, h contains the information used by R to construct the histogram, as it can be seen by printing

print(h)

## $counts

## [6] 2.403846e-06 0.000000e+00 2.403846e-06

The variable mids contains the breaks of the bin. From this we infer that the width of the bins is 2000 units (or 2 mil. USD). Thus:

sum(h$density*2000)

Box plot

The box plot describes the sample distribution. The box in the figure is the data corresponding to the 1th and 3rd quartile while the line inside the box is the 2nd quartile (i.e., the median). The whiskers extend out from the box such that the lowest datum is still within 1.5 * IQR of the lower quartile, and the highest datum is still within 1.5 * IQR of the upper quartile. Dots outside the whiskers can be interpreted as outlier.

boxplot(ceo$roe)

Empirical Cumulative density function

Another way to represent the sample data is via the empirical cumulative density function (ecdf). The R function to calculate the ecdf is ecdf. This function returns an object of class ecdf, which is basically a function that can be evaluated at different values.

x <- rnorm(100)
Psi <- ecdf(x)
Psi(-1.64)  ## should be around 0.05 for large n
## [1] 0.07

Think of evaluating the ecdf at each value in the support of the sample data e then plot \((\Psi(x), x)\) on a cartesian. This can be done easily by using the plot method for object of class ecdf. Here we plot the ecdf (in black) and the asymptotic version (i.e., the cdf of r.v. distributed as a \(N(0,1)\)).

plot(Psi)
curve(pnorm, col = "red", lty = 2, add = TRUE)

We now applied the ecdf to the ceo data, and specifically to the roe variable. We compare the ecdf of roe (in black) with the cdf of a Normal distribution with the sample mean and sample standard deviation of ceo$roe: \(N(mean(ceo\$roe),sd(ceo\$roe))\) (in red).

As can be seen from the figure below, the left tail of the sample is more pronounced of the normal distribution (when the sample mean and standard deviation are used).

plot(ecdf(ceo$roe), main = "ROE ecdf", xlab = "roe")
curve(pnorm(x, mean = mean(ceo$roe), sd = sd(ceo$roe)), col = "red", lty = 2, add = TRUE)
legend(x = 45, y = 0.2, legend = c("ecdf", "Normal cdf"), lty = c(1,2), col = c("black", "red"), bty = "n")

There are many possible way to construct the test statistic in . The apparently simple way is to calculate each individual statistic involved in \[ \frac{\overline{roe}_{c}-\overline{roe}_{nc}}{ \sqrt{\frac{s^2_{c}}{n_{c}} + \frac{s^2_{nc}}{n_{nc}}}}. \] The following code details these steps.

roe_c <- with(ceo, roe[consprod==1])  ## subset ceo according to consprod
roe_n <- with(ceo, roe[consprod==0])
nc <- length(roe_c) ## length of samples
nn <- length(roe_n)
roebar_c <- mean(roe_c) ## sector specific ROE averages 
roebar_n <- mean(roe_n)
Droe = roebar_c-roebar_n ## difference between averages 
SE   = sqrt(var(roe_c)/nc + var(roe_n)/nn) ## calculate the SE of Droe
tstat = Droe/SE ## construct test statistic
print(tstat) ## print it on screen
## [1] 5.38229

The value of the statistic is which is above the critical value of \(1.64\) for a test of size \(\alpha = 0.05\). It is also above the critical value for a test of size \(\alpha = 0.01\) which is \(2.33\). Thus, we { reject} the null hypothesis that the return on equity for consumer product company is less or equal to that of other companies in other sectors.

Alternatively, the function can be used to perform the test described. The function, part of the , has many options of options and can be called as follows:

t.test(x, y = NULL,
            alternative = c("two.sided", "less", "greater"),
            mu = 0, paired = FALSE, var.equal = FALSE,
            conf.level = 0.95, ...)

Here is a numeric vector of data values and is an optional numeric vector of data values. If is excluded, the function performs a one-sample t-test on the data contained in ; if it is included it performs a two-sample t-tests using both and .

The option provides a way to indicate the true value of the mean (or difference in means if you are performing a two sample test) under the null hypothesis. The option is a character string specifying the alternative hypothesis, and must be one of the following: “two.sided” (which is the default), “greater” or “less” depending on whether the alternative hypothesis is that the mean is different than, greater than or less than , respectively. In the two sample t-test, if the option is set to , then the statistic is calculated assuming that the variances in both groups are the same. For our roe example, the statistic reduces to \[ \frac{\overline{roe}_{c}-\overline{roe}_{nc}}{\sqrt{s^{2}\left(\frac{1}{n_{c}}+\frac{1}{n_{nc}}\right)}}, \] where \(s^2\) is the “pooled” sample variance, that is, the sample variance obtained using the whole sample. Unless there are good reasons to believe that the variance is constant across group, a test with unequal variance should be used. The set the level of the confidence interval that will output. You should let the paired option alone: when it is set to it performs a test which allows for dependence between the groups.}

For example the following call performs a one sample t-test with where the null hypothesis is that the average roe is larger or equal to \(17\) and the alternative is that it is less than \(17\).

t.test(ceo[["roe"]], alternative = "less", mu = 17)

The output of is very detailed and it is shown below.

## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  ceo[["roe"]]
## t = 0.33629, df = 207, p-value = 0.6315
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is less than 17
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##    -Inf 18.177
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  17.19905

More interestingly, this is the call to our testing problem.

t.test(x = roe_c, y = roe_n, alternative = "greater", mu = 0)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  roe_c and roe_n
## t = 5.3823, df = 79.919, p-value = 3.584e-07
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is greater than 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  5.29703     Inf
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  22.65501  14.98717

Notice that our ``manual’’ calculations coincide with those of , but from this output we get way more information. For instance, we get a confidence interval and a { \(p\)-value}. Low values of the \(p\)-value indicate that the null hypothesis should be rejected. In particular, if the \(p\)-value is { less then} \(\alpha\), then the null hypothesis can be rejected (at the \(\alpha\times 100\%\) significance level).

We can calculate the p-value by ``hand’’ with following code.

1-pt(tstat, df = 79.919)
## [1] 3.584259e-07

Regression

We already saw how to draw a scatter plot. New we want to add a regression line to this graph (and we want also start making graphs look nicer).

with(ceo, plot(pcroe, salary, pch = 19, col = "darkgreen"))
abline(lm(salary~pcroe, data = ceo), col = "darkblue", lwd = 1.5, lty = 2)

The regression line is added by the call to abline, but what is interesting is that the argument to abline is another function call lm(...). Indeed, lm, which stands for linear model is a powerful function with many options, but to quickly running a regression between two variables is relatively easy

lm(salary~pcroe, data = ceo) 
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = salary ~ pcroe, data = ceo)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)        pcroe  
##   1277.7094       0.4163

The pcsalary~pcroe is a formula and tells lm to run the following regression \[salary_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 pcroe_i + u_i,\]. The data to run the regression is to be found in the data.frame passed to data, in this case roe. Using formula is a very flexible way to specify models. For instance, we can remove the intercept from the model pcsalary ~ pcroe-1 and/or we can make other interesting trasformation to the variables. For instance. the formula log(salary)~pcroe specifies the following model \[\log(salary_i) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 pcroe_i + u_i.\]

Invoked directly (as was done above) the function returns the estimated coefficients and little else. We can also assign the results of the call to a variable.

lm_1 <- lm(pcsalary~pcroe, data = ceo) 
class(lm_1)
## [1] "lm"

lm_1 is an object of class lm to which several methods are defined. For instance, we can extract the coefficient (coef), an estimate of the variance of the coefficients (vcov), and the residuals (residuals). The standard errors are the square root of the diagonal element sof the estimated variance.

coef(lm_1)
## (Intercept)       pcroe 
## 12.52815423  0.06980514
vcov(lm_1)
##              (Intercept)         pcroe
## (Intercept)  5.002409598 -0.0054369433
## pcroe       -0.005436943  0.0005257724
sqrt(diag(vcov(lm_1)))  ## standard errors
## (Intercept)       pcroe 
##  2.23660672  0.02292973
head(resid(lm_1))
##          1          2          3          4          5          6 
##  21.607884  -2.390330 -19.734161  -5.318739  -7.597959  -2.116304
